lack Infant Mortality: Continuities, Contestations and Care -- tPart IV: The Institutional Matrix of Health Care -- tIntroduction -- t16 The Regional and Racial Politics of Postwar Hospitals -- t17 Health Activism in the 1960s and the Community Health Center System -- t18 The Veterans Administration and PTSD: Challenges and Changes from Vietnam to Iraq -- t19 The Pharmaceutical Industry, Drug Regulation and US Health Services -- t20 The National Institutes of Health: Courting Congress, Creating a Research Infrastructure -- tPart V: The White House, Congress and Health Reform -- tIntroduction -- t21 Left Out: Health Security and the American Welfare State, 1935–50 -- t22 Medicare and Medicaid after the Great Society: Containing Costs, Expanding Coverage -- t23 Mental Health, Stigma and Federal Reform in the 1970s and 1990s -- t24 The War on Drugs: Nixon, Reagan, Trump -- t25 Obamacare and Its Critics -- tPart VI: Justice, Ethics and American Health -- tIntroduction -- t26 Roe v. Wade and the Cultural Politics of Abortion: The Shift from Rights to Health -- t27 Genetics, Health and the Making of America’s Triracial Isolates, 1950–80 -- t28 The Rhetoric and Politics of American Ageism: Notes from a Pandemic -- t29 Towards a Structural Competency Framework for Addressing US Gun Violence -- t30 Mass Incarceration and Health Inequity in the United States -- tPart VII: Public Health and Global Health -- tIntroduction -- t31 Occupational and Environmental Health in Twentieth-Century America -- t32 Environmental Health beyond the State: Thinking through the 1970s -- t33 Bioterrorism, Pandemic and the American Public -- t34 Health Internationalism in the US and Beyond -- t35 Pandemics and the Politics of Planetary Health -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamines the diverse, and often conflicted, political status of health in the United States from World War II to Covid-19Explores the histories, cultures, policies and technologies of American health and medicine as they have developed over a 75-year periodBrings together 45 experts from the US, Canada and the UK working across the fields of medicine, health policy, political and social history, political science, environmental studies, law, and cultural studiesUses the lenses of class, poverty, race, gender, sexuality and locality to study the concepts, policies and lived realities of U.S. healthcare and medical treatmentExplores key controversies in American health, including global health and new technologiesBy emphasising the plurality of health experiences, and balancing national and transnational perspectives with the lived realities of diverse communities, this groundbreaking collection expands far beyond biomedical conceptions of health. Together, the contributors take a multi-layered view of the politics of US healthcare by examining it from historical, cultural, medical, sociological, legal, ethical and environmental perspectives. Chapters consider major health institutions and the federal policies that guide them; the intersection between health and social movements; the contours of health and illness with respect to race, gender, sexuality, age and region; and the US’s often-conflicted role in global health governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedical carexHistoryzUnited States. 0aMedical carezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMedical policyxHistoryzUnited States. 0aMedical policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aPolitics. 7aHISTORY / North America.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Melanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirn, Anne-Emanuelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/